{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b2c800b8-13a2-4f43-9574-89693792613c","content":"A **NullReferenceException** is a runtime application bug — it means your code is dereferencing a `null` value. CLR activation logs won't help here; they diagnose issues with **loading the .NET runtime itself** (e.g., wrong runtime version selected, missing runtime, shim failures).\n\n**To diagnose your NullReferenceException**, you need:\n\n1. **The stack trace** from the exception — it tells you exactly which line has the null dereference.\n2. **The code** at that location — to identify which variable is null and why.\n\nCould you share:\n- The **full exception message and stack trace**?\n- The **relevant source code** (or point me to it in a repo)?\n\nIf you *also* have a CLR activation/loading problem (e.g., the app fails to start at all, picks the wrong runtime, or shows a missing framework dialog), I can help with that too — just share the activation log file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c11dd192-f1fb-41f3-a4af-ef49974b19e4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. However, they haven't provided any CLR activation logs, and there don't appear to be any files in the current working directory to analyze.\n\nLet me check if there are any files in the current directory first, and also note that CLR activation logs are about runtime loading/binding, not about NullReferenceExceptions. These are different concerns.\n\nLet me check the directory first.","outputTokens":345,"requestId":"6401:311A36:E3838BA:FCF5165:69EC177A"},"id":"96a6d2f8-f052-4a58-bdd3-4ea280ee86ef","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:23:16.104Z","parentId":"0ed928d5-29fd-4a8f-9265-180b57c1a4fe"}
